body:
Tailwind CSS is powerful but easy to misuse. Long class strings, repeated patterns, and inconsistent spacing are the most common problems. Here are 10 patterns that keep Tailwind code clean and maintainable.

## 1. Extract Components, Not Classes

The biggest Tailwind mistake: using `@apply` to extract utility classes into CSS. Instead, extract React components:

```jsx
// Bad — @apply in CSS
.btn-primary {
  @apply px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-700;
}

// Good — React component
function Button({ children, onClick, variant = 'primary' }) {
  const styles = {
    primary: 'px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-blue-700',
    secondary: 'px-4 py-2 bg-gray-100 text-gray-900 rounded-lg hover:bg-gray-200',
  }
  return (
    <button onClick={onClick} className={styles[variant]}>
      {children}
    </button>
  )
}
```

## 2. Use the `cn` Utility for Conditional Classes

```bash
npm install clsx tailwind-merge
```

```javascript
import { clsx } from 'clsx'
import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge'

export function cn(...inputs) {
  return twMerge(clsx(inputs))
}
```

Usage:

```jsx
<div className={cn(
  'px-4 py-2 rounded-lg',
  isActive && 'bg-blue-600 text-white',
  isDisabled && 'opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed',
  className // allow overrides from parent
)}>
```

## 3. Responsive Design with Mobile-First

Tailwind is mobile-first. Unprefixed classes apply to all sizes, prefixed classes apply at that breakpoint and above:

```jsx
<div className="
  grid grid-cols-1        // mobile: 1 column
  md:grid-cols-2          // tablet: 2 columns
  lg:grid-cols-3          // desktop: 3 columns
  gap-4 md:gap-6 lg:gap-8 // responsive gap
">
```

## 4. Dark Mode

Enable dark mode in `tailwind.config.js`:

```javascript
export default {
  darkMode: 'class', // toggle with class on <html>
  // ...
}
```

Usage:

```jsx
<div className="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
```

Toggle:

```javascript
document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark')
```

## 5. Custom Design Tokens

Extend Tailwind with your brand colors and spacing:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
export default {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        brand: {
          50: '#eff6ff',
          500: '#3b82f6',
          900: '#1e3a8a',
        }
      },
      fontFamily: {
        sans: ['Inter', 'system-ui', 'sans-serif'],
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Now use `text-brand-500`, `bg-brand-50`, etc.

## 6. Group and Peer Modifiers

Style children based on parent state:

```jsx
// group — style children when parent is hovered
<div className="group cursor-pointer">
  <h3 className="text-gray-900 group-hover:text-blue-600">Title</h3>
  <p className="text-gray-500 group-hover:text-gray-700">Description</p>
</div>

// peer — style siblings based on input state
<input type="checkbox" className="peer hidden" />
<label className="peer-checked:text-blue-600 peer-checked:font-bold">Option</label>
```

## 7. Arbitrary Values

For one-off values that aren't in the scale:

```jsx
<div className="w-[342px] h-[calc(100vh-64px)] bg-[#1a1a2e]">
```

Use sparingly — if you're using arbitrary values everywhere, you probably need custom tokens.

## 8. Animation

```jsx
// Built-in animations
<div className="animate-spin">Loading...</div>
<div className="animate-pulse">Skeleton</div>
<div className="animate-bounce">Bounce</div>

// Custom animation
// tailwind.config.js
extend: {
  animation: {
    'fade-in': 'fadeIn 0.3s ease-in-out',
  },
  keyframes: {
    fadeIn: {
      '0%': { opacity: '0', transform: 'translateY(10px)' },
      '100%': { opacity: '1', transform: 'translateY(0)' },
    }
  }
}
```

## 9. Avoid Long Class Strings

When a class string gets long, break it across lines with a template literal:

```jsx
const cardStyles = [
  'rounded-xl border border-gray-200',
  'bg-white shadow-sm',
  'p-6 flex flex-col gap-4',
  'hover:shadow-md transition-shadow duration-200',
].join(' ')

<div className={cardStyles}>
```

## 10. Purge Unused Styles

Tailwind automatically purges unused classes in production when you configure `content`:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
export default {
  content: [
    './index.html',
    './src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}',
  ],
  // ...
}
```

This keeps your CSS bundle tiny (usually 5-20KB in production).

## The Rule of Thumb

If you're copying the same class string more than twice, extract a component. If you're fighting the design system, add a custom token. If you're writing `@apply`, stop and make a React component instead.
